{"id":"2010.02888","submitter":"Maryam Aliakbarpour","authors":"Maryam Aliakbarpour, Amartya Shankha Biswas, Kavya Ravichandran,\n  Ronitt Rubinfeld","title":"Testing Tail Weight of a Distribution Via Hazard Rate","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.LG math.ST stat.ML stat.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Understanding the shape of a distribution of data is of interest to people in\na great variety of fields, as it may affect the types of algorithms used for\nthat data. We study one such problem in the framework of distribution property\ntesting, characterizing the number of samples required to to distinguish\nwhether a distribution has a certain property or is far from having that\nproperty. In particular, given samples from a distribution, we seek to\ncharacterize the tail of the distribution, that is, understand how many\nelements appear infrequently. We develop an algorithm based on a careful\nbucketing scheme that distinguishes light-tailed distributions from\nnon-light-tailed ones with respect to a definition based on the hazard rate,\nunder natural smoothness and ordering assumptions. We bound the number of\nsamples required for this test to succeed with high probability in terms of the\nparameters of the problem, showing that it is polynomial in these parameters.\nFurther, we prove a hardness result that implies that this problem cannot be\nsolved without any assumptions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Oct 2020 17:13:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 4 Dec 2022 18:47:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-06"}
